==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sheer
<hw>Sheer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>shere</ets>,
<ets>skere</ets>, pure, bright, Icel. <ets>sk<?/rr</ets>; akin to
<ets>sk⟦imac⟧rr</ets>, AS. <ets>sc⟦imac⟧r</ets>, OS.
<ets>sk⟦imac⟧ri</ets>, MHG. <ets>sch⟦imac⟧r</ets>, G. <ets>schier</ets>,
Dan. <ets>sk<?/r</ets>, Sw. <ets>sk⟦aum⟧r</ets>, Goth. <ets>skeirs</ets>
clear, and E. <ets>shine</ets>. ⟦root⟧157. See <er>Shine</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Bright; clear; pure; unmixed.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Sheer</xex> ale.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou <qex>sheer</qex>, immaculate, and silver fountain.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Very thin or transparent; -- applied to fabrics;
<as>as, <ex>sheer</ex> muslin</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Being only what it seems to be; obvious; simple;
mere; downright; <as>as, <ex>sheer</ex> folly; <ex>sheer</ex>
nonsense</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>sheer</xex> impossibility.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>De Quincey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is not a <qex>sheer</qex> advantage to have several strings to
one's bow.</q> <rj><qau>M. Arnold.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Stright up and down; vertical;
prpendicular.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>sheer</qex> precipice of a thousand feet.</q> <rj><qau>J.
D. Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was at least⟦br⟧
Nine roods of <qex>sheer</qex> ascent.</q>
<rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sheer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sheer
<hw>Sheer</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Clean; quite; at once.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sheer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sheer
<hw>Sheer</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Shear</er>.]</ety>
<def>To shear.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sheer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Sheer
<hw>Sheer</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sheered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sheering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[D. <ets>sheren</ets> to shear,
cut, withdraw, warp. See <er>Shear</er>.]</ety> <def>To decline or
deviate from the line of the proper course; to turn aside; to swerve;
<as>as, a ship <ex>sheers</ex> from her course; a horse <ex>sheers</ex>
at a bicycle</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To sheer off</b></col>, <cd>to turn or move aside to a
distance; to move away.</cd> -- <col><b>To sheer up</b></col>, <cd>to
approach obliquely.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sheer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Sheer
<hw>Sheer</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>
<sd>(a)</sd> <def>The longitudinal upward curvature of the deck,
gunwale, and lines of a vessel, as when viewed from the side.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>The position of a vessel riding at single anchor and
swinging clear of it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A turn or change in a course.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Give the canoe a <qex>sheer</qex> and get nearer to the shore.</q>
<rj><qau>Cooper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Shears See
<er>Shear</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sheer batten</b></col> <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld>, <cd>a
long strip of wood to guide the carpenters in following the sheer
plan.</cd> -- <col><b>Sheer boom</b></col>, <cd>a boom slanting across a
stream to direct floating logs to one side.</cd> -- <col><b>Sheer
hulk</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>Shear hulk</cref>, under
<er>Hulk</er>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Sheer plan</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Sheer draught</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld>, <cd>a
projection of the lines of a vessel on a vertical longitudinal plane
passing through the middle line of the vessel.</cd> -- <col><b>Sheer
pole</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>an iron rod lashed to the shrouds
just above the dead-eyes and parallel to the ratlines.</cd> --
<col><b>Sheer strake</b></col> <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld>, <cd>the strake
under the gunwale on the top side.</cd> <au>Totten.</au> -- <col><b>To
break sheer</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to deviate from sheer, and
risk fouling the anchor.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sheerly</ent>⟦br⟧
